{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QJHz3yqxKdYaDvxHFZskPg","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 10 — Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Correction to Feedback Root Cause (Failure 1)\n     4→\n     5→The feedback states that \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" has 6 words and gets penalized by the pre-filter's `wordCount <= 5` sort. This is incorrect — the title has **5 words** (CHLEBEK, Z, WARZYWAMI, I, BOCZKIEM), so `wordCount(text) <= 5` is true and it sorts into the highest-priority tier alongside other short ALL_CAPS candidates. The pre-filter does not cut it.\n     6→\n     7→The actual root cause is a **structural heading mis-selection combined with dedup**:\n     8→\n     9→1. Both \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (position 1) and \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" (position 2) qualify as structural headings via `isStructuralHeading`.\n    10→2. `bestStructural` is selected by `rawScore`. If MiniLM rates \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" higher (plausible — it's a tighter food phrase that may embed closer to the title reference), it wins the structural heading slot.\n    11→3. `firstStructuralHeading` = \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\". The prefix filter at line 440 then removes prefixes of \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\", not prefixes of the real title.\n    12→4. \"CHLEBEK\" (position 8, a sub-section header for the bread part) is **not** a prefix of \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\", so it survives the prefix filter.\n    13→5. Dedup at line 489: \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" contains \"CHLEBEK\" (shorter) → the real title is removed. \"CHLEBEK\" wins.\n    14→\n    15→The prefix filter is structurally correct but depends on `bestStructural` being the real title — a precondition the algorithm cannot guarantee with cross-lingual embeddings.\n    16→\n    17→---\n    18→\n    19→## Fix 1: Polish Metadata Patterns in `looksLikeMetadata`\n    20→\n    21→### Root cause\n    22→Polish recipe conventions use patterns invisible to the English-only metadata regex:\n    23→- **Serving size**: \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" (for 3 peppers), \"NA OKOŁO 1 ½ KG\" (for about 1.5 kg), \"DLA 4 OSÓB\" (for 4 people)\n    24→- **Time metadata**: \"PRZYGOTOWANIE 1 GODZ. 45 MIN\", \"GOTOWANIE 30 MIN\", \"OCZEKIWANIE 1 GODZ. 30 MIN\"\n    25→- **OCR-corrupted time metadata**: \"PRZYGOTOWANTE 20 MIN\" (E→A), \"GOTOMANTE 15 MIN\" (OWANIE→MANTE)\n    26→\n    27→These survive all hard filters, enter the candidate pool, accumulate ALL_CAPS bonus, and compete with real titles.\n    28→\n    29→### Specific changes\n    30→\n    31→Add to `METADATA_PATTERNS` in `title-extractor.ts`:\n    32→\n    33→**Before:**\n    34→```typescript\n    35→const METADATA_PATTERNS = [\n    36→  /^(SERVES?|MAKES?|YIELDS?)\\b/i,\n    37→  /^(PREP(ARATION)?|COOK(ING)?|PROOF|RISING|FERMENTATION|REST(ING)?)\\s*(AND\\s*)?(COOK(ING)?)?\\s*TIME/i,\n    38→  /^SAMPLE\\s+SCHEDULE\\b/i,\n    39→  /^BULK\\s+FERMENTATION\\b/i,\n    40→  /^(THIS\\s+RECIPE\\s+)?MAKES\\b/i,\n    41→];\n    42→```\n    43→\n    44→**After:**\n    45→```typescript\n    46→const METADATA_PATTERNS = [\n    47→  /^(SERVES?|MAKES?|YIELDS?)\\b/i,\n    48→  /^(PREP(ARATION)?|COOK(ING)?|PROOF|RISING|FERMENTATION|REST(ING)?)\\s*(AND\\s*)?(COOK(ING)?)?\\s*TIME/i,\n    49→  /^SAMPLE\\s+SCHEDULE\\b/i,\n    50→  /^BULK\\s+FERMENTATION\\b/i,\n    51→  /^(THIS\\s+RECIPE\\s+)?MAKES\\b/i,\n    52→  // Polish serving-size patterns: \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\", \"NA OKOŁO 1 KG\", \"DLA 4 OSÓB\"\n    53→  /^NA\\s+(\\d|OKOŁO)\\b/i,\n    54→  /^DLA\\s+\\d/i,\n    55→  // Time-unit metadata: any line containing \"N MIN\" or \"N GODZ\" is prep/cook/rest time,\n    56→  // regardless of OCR-corrupted prefix (catches PRZYGOTOWANTE, GOTOMANTE, etc.)\n    57→  /\\b\\d+\\s*MIN\\b/i,\n    58→  /\\b\\d+\\s*GODZ/i,\n    59→];\n    60→```\n    61→\n    62→### Why time-unit patterns are safe as metadata filters\n    63→\n    64→Could `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN\\b` accidentally filter a legitimate recipe title? No:\n    65→- \"30 Minute Bread\" starts with a digit → already rejected by `startsWithNumber`\n    66→- \"MINESTRONE\" has \"MIN\" but no preceding digit → doesn't match\n    67→- \"5 MIN NOODLES\" starts with digit → already rejected\n    68→- In the entire 10-iteration test corpus, no legitimate title contains \"digit + MIN\" or \"digit + GODZ\"\n    69→\n    70→### Impact on test cases\n    71→\n    72→| Candidate | Pattern matched | Effect |\n    73→|---|---|---|\n    74→| \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" | `^NA\\s+\\d` | **Filtered** — fixes Failure 2 directly |\n    75→| \"NA OKOŁO 1 ½ KG\" | `^NA\\s+OKOŁO` | Filtered — correct for Kimchi input |\n    76→| \"DLA 4 OSÓB\" / \"DLA 4 OSOB\" | `^DLA\\s+\\d` | Filtered — reduces noise in CHLEBEK and MŁODE PORY |\n    77→| \"PRZYGOTOWANIE 1 GODZ. 45 MIN\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` (via \"45 MIN\") | Filtered |\n    78→| \"GOTOWANIE 30 MIN\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` | Filtered |\n    79→| \"OCZEKIWANIE 1 GODZ. 30 MIN\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` | Filtered |\n    80→| \"PRZYGOTOWANTE 20 MIN\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` | **Filtered** — catches OCR error |\n    81→| \"GOTOMANTE 15 MIN\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` | **Filtered** — catches OCR error |\n    82→| \"PIECZENIE 30 MINUT\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` | Filtered (hypothetical) |\n    83→| \"Leżakowanie\" | none (no digit) | Not filtered — correct |\n    84→\n    85→### Expected impact on Failure 2\n    86→\n    87→With \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" filtered as metadata, the candidates for \"Faszerowana papryka.real.txt\" become:\n    88→- \"Faszerowana papryka\" (position 0, mixed-case)\n    89→- \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" (position 1, ALL_CAPS)\n    90→- \"SKŁADNIKI\" (position 9, single-word ALL_CAPS)\n    91→- \"WARZYWA\" (position 25, single-word ALL_CAPS)\n    92→- Various body text joins\n    93→\n    94→The bilingual suppression correctly fires (position-0 mixed-case + position-1 ALL_CAPS with semantic similarity > 0.4). \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" is suppressed from threshold computation. \"Faszerowana papryka\" wins.\n    95→\n    96→---\n    97→\n    98→## Fix 2: Pre-dedup Sub-section Header Removal\n    99→\n   100→### Root cause\n   101→\n   102→The dedup rule at line 489 unconditionally prefers shorter candidates when one is a substring of another. This is correct for most cases (e.g., \"Pierogi Ruskie\" over \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\") but destructive when a short **sub-section header** shares words with the actual title.\n   103→\n   104→In the CHLEBEK case: \"CHLEBEK\" (position 8) is a sub-section header for the bread portion of the recipe. It is a substring of the actual title \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (position 1). The dedup rule removes the real title.\n   105→\n   106→The existing prefix filter at line 440 was designed to handle this, but it only removes prefixes of `firstStructuralHeading`. When `bestStructural` resolves to \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" instead of the real title (due to cross-lingual embedding noise), the prefix filter targets the wrong heading and \"CHLEBEK\" survives.\n   107→\n   108→### Specific changes\n   109→\n   110→Add a pre-dedup filter between the continuation join protection (line 482) and the dedup (line 489). The filter identifies **sub-section headers**: ALL_CAPS candidates that are followed in the source document by ingredient-like content.\n   111→\n   112→**Insert after line 482, before the dedup block:**\n   113→\n   114→```typescript\n   115→// Pre-dedup: remove sub-section headers that are substrings of other surviving candidates.\n   116→// A sub-section header is an ALL_CAPS candidate followed by ingredient-like lines in the source.\n   117→// Example: \"CHLEBEK\" (bread section header, followed by \"500 g mąki\") is a substring of\n   118→// \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (the real title). Without this filter, dedup kills the title.\n   119→selected = selected.filter((candidate) => {\n   120→  if (!isAllCaps(candidate.text)) return true;\n   121→  // Check if this candidate is followed by ingredient-like content\n   122→  const nextSourceLines = lines.slice(candidate.position + 1, candidate.position + 3);\n   123→  const followedByIngredients = nextSourceLines.some(\n   124→    (l) => looksLikeIngredient(l.trim()) || /^\\s*\\d/.test(l.trim())\n   125→  );\n   126→  if (!followedByIngredients) return true;\n   127→  // Only remove if a longer candidate contains this one as a substring\n   128→  const candidateLower = candidate.text.toLowerCase();\n   129→  const hasLongerParent = selected.some(\n   130→    (other) =>\n   131→      other !== candidate &&\n   132→      other.text.length > candidate.text.length &&\n   133→      other.text.toLowerCase().includes(candidateLower)\n   134→  );\n   135→  return !hasLongerParent;\n   136→});\n   137→```\n   138→\n   139→### Why this is safe\n   140→\n   141→The filter requires **three conditions** to fire simultaneously:\n   142→1. The candidate is ALL_CAPS\n   143→2. It is followed by ingredient-like lines (strong sub-section signal)\n   144→3. A longer candidate containing it as a substring also survived threshold\n   145→\n   146→This is conservative — it only resolves the specific conflict where a sub-section header's name overlaps with the title. It cannot remove standalone titles because condition (3) requires a longer superset candidate to exist.\n   147→\n   148→### Regression analysis\n   149→\n   150→| Test case | Effect |\n   151→|---|---|\n   152→| ARAYES SHRAK | \"ARAYES\" (1 word) doesn't survive threshold independently — never reaches dedup. No change. |\n   153→| Baked Eggs | No ALL_CAPS sub-section headers that are substrings of the title. No change. |\n   154→| CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM | **\"CHLEBEK\" removed** — followed by \"500 g mąki\" (ingredient) and is substring of real title. Fix applied. |\n   155→| Finnish Flatbreads | Two separate recipe titles, neither is a substring of the other. No change. |\n   156→| Faszerowana papryka | Already fixed by Fix 1 (NA 3 PAPRYKI filtered). No sub-section header conflict. No change. |\n   157→| MIXED SEED CRISPBREAD | No sub-section header conflicts. No change. |\n   158→| OVERNIGHT STRAIGHT PIZZA DOUGH | No sub-section header conflicts. No change. |\n   159→| SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS | No sub-section header conflicts. No change. |\n   160→| Kimchi z ogórków | \"SKŁADNIKI\" is ALL_CAPS and followed by ingredients, but no longer candidate contains \"SKŁADNIKI\". Condition (3) fails. No change. |\n   161→| MŁODE PORY DUSZONE W PIWIE | No ALL_CAPS sub-section headers that are substrings of the title. No change. |\n   162→\n   163→### Expected impact on Failure 1\n   164→\n   165→With Fix 1 removing \"DLA 4 OSÓB\", \"PRZYGOTOWANIE 1 GODZ. 45 MIN\", \"GOTOWANIE 30 MIN\", and \"OCZEKIWANIE 1 GODZ. 30 MIN\" from the candidate pool, the remaining ALL_CAPS candidates are:\n   166→- \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (position 1)\n   167→- \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" (position 2)\n   168→- \"CHLEBEK\" (position 8)\n   169→\n   170→Fix 1 alone helps by reducing noise, but the core CHLEBEK/dedup issue persists. Fix 2 then removes \"CHLEBEK\" because:\n   171→- It's ALL_CAPS ✓\n   172→- Followed by \"500 g mąki\" (ingredient) ✓\n   173→- \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" contains \"CHLEBEK\" and is longer ✓\n   174→\n   175→Similarly, \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" at position 2 is followed by \"500 g strączków zielonego groszku\" (ingredient) and is a substring of \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" — wait, no. Is \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" a substring of \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"? \"warzywa i boczek\" vs \"chlebek z warzywami i boczkiem\" — no, \"warzywami\" ≠ \"warzywa\". So condition (3) fails for \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\". It survives.\n   176→\n   177→Final candidates after Fix 2: \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" and \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\". The multi-title guard (line 504) fires with 2 ALL_CAPS candidates. `isSubHeader` checks if \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" (the non-first) is followed by ingredients → yes → `isSubHeader = true` → collapses to `[sortedCaps[0]]` = \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (position 1 < position 2).\n   178→\n   179→Result: **\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"** — correct.\n   180→\n   181→---\n   182→\n   183→## Fix 3: Structural Heading Selection Robustness (Optional)\n   184→\n   185→### Root cause\n   186→\n   187→`bestStructural` is chosen purely by `rawScore`, which depends on MiniLM cross-lingual embedding quality. For Polish text, the model may not reliably rank a 5-word compound title above a 3-word food phrase. This makes the downstream prefix filter fragile.\n   188→\n   189→### Specific changes\n   190→\n   191→Add a tiebreaker to `bestStructural` selection: when rawScores are within 0.03 of each other, prefer the candidate with more words (longer title = more specific = more likely the actual title, not a section header). If word counts are also equal, prefer the earlier position.\n   192→\n   193→**Before:**\n   194→```typescript\n   195→const bestStructural = structuralCandidates.length > 0\n   196→  ? structuralCandidates.reduce((a, b) => a.rawScore > b.rawScore ? a : b)\n   197→  : null;\n   198→```\n   199→\n   200→**After:**\n   201→```typescript\n   202→const bestStructural = structuralCandidates.length > 0\n   203→  ? structuralCandidates.reduce((a, b) => {\n   204→      const scoreDiff = a.rawScore - b.rawScore;\n   205→      if (Math.abs(scoreDiff) > 0.03) return scoreDiff > 0 ? a : b;\n   206→      // Tiebreak: more words (more specific) → better\n   207→      const wcDiff = wordCount(b.text) - wordCount(a.text);\n   208→      if (wcDiff !== 0) return wcDiff > 0 ? b : a;\n   209→      // Tiebreak: earlier position → better\n   210→      return a.position < b.position ? a : b;\n   211→    })\n   212→  : null;\n   213→```\n   214→\n   215→This makes the prefix filter at line 440 more likely to target the correct (longer, more specific) heading, providing defense-in-depth alongside Fix 2. With a 0.03 threshold, a clearly better rawScore still wins.\n   216→\n   217→### Risk assessment\n   218→\n   219→Low risk. Only changes behavior when two structural headings have nearly identical rawScores (within 0.03). In that case, preferring the longer/earlier candidate is almost always correct — a sub-section header is never the title when a longer heading containing the same topic exists.\n   220→\n   221→---\n   222→\n   223→## Summary\n   224→\n   225→| Fix | Addresses | Mechanism | Risk |\n   226→|---|---|---|---|\n   227→| **Fix 1**: Polish metadata patterns | Failure 2 directly; reduces Failure 1 noise | Hard filter in `looksLikeMetadata` | Very low — patterns are specific and well-attested |\n   228→| **Fix 2**: Pre-dedup sub-section removal | Failure 1 directly | Pre-dedup filter gated on 3 conditions | Low — conservative triple-condition gate |\n   229→| **Fix 3**: Structural heading tiebreaker | Failure 1 (defense-in-depth) | Tiebreaker with 0.03 threshold | Very low — only changes close-call decisions |\n   230→\n   231→### Expected accuracy after fixes\n   232→\n   233→All 8 existing test cases should pass. The 2 new test cases (Kimchi z ogórków, MŁODE PORY DUSZONE W PIWIE) should also benefit from the Polish metadata patterns.\n   234→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"84856199-2e39-4e5f-88ee-7f061b951e03","uuid":"d464a3fd-87ab-4ce8-be82-e2ba9ba6b449","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/10-d73df28/improvement-plan.md","content":"# Iteration 10 — Improvement Plan\n\n## Correction to Feedback Root Cause (Failure 1)\n\nThe feedback states that \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" has 6 words and gets penalized by the pre-filter's `wordCount <= 5` sort. This is incorrect — the title has **5 words** (CHLEBEK, Z, WARZYWAMI, I, BOCZKIEM), so `wordCount(text) <= 5` is true and it sorts into the highest-priority tier alongside other short ALL_CAPS candidates. The pre-filter does not cut it.\n\nThe actual root cause is a **structural heading mis-selection combined with dedup**:\n\n1. Both \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (position 1) and \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" (position 2) qualify as structural headings via `isStructuralHeading`.\n2. `bestStructural` is selected by `rawScore`. If MiniLM rates \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" higher (plausible — it's a tighter food phrase that may embed closer to the title reference), it wins the structural heading slot.\n3. `firstStructuralHeading` = \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\". The prefix filter at line 440 then removes prefixes of \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\", not prefixes of the real title.\n4. \"CHLEBEK\" (position 8, a sub-section header for the bread part) is **not** a prefix of \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\", so it survives the prefix filter.\n5. Dedup at line 489: \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" contains \"CHLEBEK\" (shorter) → the real title is removed. \"CHLEBEK\" wins.\n\nThe prefix filter is structurally correct but depends on `bestStructural` being the real title — a precondition the algorithm cannot guarantee with cross-lingual embeddings.\n\n---\n\n## Fix 1: Polish Metadata Patterns in `looksLikeMetadata`\n\n### Root cause\nPolish recipe conventions use patterns invisible to the English-only metadata regex:\n- **Serving size**: \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" (for 3 peppers), \"NA OKOŁO 1 ½ KG\" (for about 1.5 kg), \"DLA 4 OSÓB\" (for 4 people)\n- **Time metadata**: \"PRZYGOTOWANIE 1 GODZ. 45 MIN\", \"GOTOWANIE 30 MIN\", \"OCZEKIWANIE 1 GODZ. 30 MIN\"\n- **OCR-corrupted time metadata**: \"PRZYGOTOWANTE 20 MIN\" (E→A), \"GOTOMANTE 15 MIN\" (OWANIE→MANTE)\n\nThese survive all hard filters, enter the candidate pool, accumulate ALL_CAPS bonus, and compete with real titles.\n\n### Specific changes\n\nAdd to `METADATA_PATTERNS` in `title-extractor.ts`:\n\n**Before:**\n```typescript\nconst METADATA_PATTERNS = [\n  /^(SERVES?|MAKES?|YIELDS?)\\b/i,\n  /^(PREP(ARATION)?|COOK(ING)?|PROOF|RISING|FERMENTATION|REST(ING)?)\\s*(AND\\s*)?(COOK(ING)?)?\\s*TIME/i,\n  /^SAMPLE\\s+SCHEDULE\\b/i,\n  /^BULK\\s+FERMENTATION\\b/i,\n  /^(THIS\\s+RECIPE\\s+)?MAKES\\b/i,\n];\n```\n\n**After:**\n```typescript\nconst METADATA_PATTERNS = [\n  /^(SERVES?|MAKES?|YIELDS?)\\b/i,\n  /^(PREP(ARATION)?|COOK(ING)?|PROOF|RISING|FERMENTATION|REST(ING)?)\\s*(AND\\s*)?(COOK(ING)?)?\\s*TIME/i,\n  /^SAMPLE\\s+SCHEDULE\\b/i,\n  /^BULK\\s+FERMENTATION\\b/i,\n  /^(THIS\\s+RECIPE\\s+)?MAKES\\b/i,\n  // Polish serving-size patterns: \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\", \"NA OKOŁO 1 KG\", \"DLA 4 OSÓB\"\n  /^NA\\s+(\\d|OKOŁO)\\b/i,\n  /^DLA\\s+\\d/i,\n  // Time-unit metadata: any line containing \"N MIN\" or \"N GODZ\" is prep/cook/rest time,\n  // regardless of OCR-corrupted prefix (catches PRZYGOTOWANTE, GOTOMANTE, etc.)\n  /\\b\\d+\\s*MIN\\b/i,\n  /\\b\\d+\\s*GODZ/i,\n];\n```\n\n### Why time-unit patterns are safe as metadata filters\n\nCould `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN\\b` accidentally filter a legitimate recipe title? No:\n- \"30 Minute Bread\" starts with a digit → already rejected by `startsWithNumber`\n- \"MINESTRONE\" has \"MIN\" but no preceding digit → doesn't match\n- \"5 MIN NOODLES\" starts with digit → already rejected\n- In the entire 10-iteration test corpus, no legitimate title contains \"digit + MIN\" or \"digit + GODZ\"\n\n### Impact on test cases\n\n| Candidate | Pattern matched | Effect |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" | `^NA\\s+\\d` | **Filtered** — fixes Failure 2 directly |\n| \"NA OKOŁO 1 ½ KG\" | `^NA\\s+OKOŁO` | Filtered — correct for Kimchi input |\n| \"DLA 4 OSÓB\" / \"DLA 4 OSOB\" | `^DLA\\s+\\d` | Filtered — reduces noise in CHLEBEK and MŁODE PORY |\n| \"PRZYGOTOWANIE 1 GODZ. 45 MIN\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` (via \"45 MIN\") | Filtered |\n| \"GOTOWANIE 30 MIN\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` | Filtered |\n| \"OCZEKIWANIE 1 GODZ. 30 MIN\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` | Filtered |\n| \"PRZYGOTOWANTE 20 MIN\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` | **Filtered** — catches OCR error |\n| \"GOTOMANTE 15 MIN\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` | **Filtered** — catches OCR error |\n| \"PIECZENIE 30 MINUT\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` | Filtered (hypothetical) |\n| \"Leżakowanie\" | none (no digit) | Not filtered — correct |\n\n### Expected impact on Failure 2\n\nWith \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" filtered as metadata, the candidates for \"Faszerowana papryka.real.txt\" become:\n- \"Faszerowana papryka\" (position 0, mixed-case)\n- \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" (position 1, ALL_CAPS)\n- \"SKŁADNIKI\" (position 9, single-word ALL_CAPS)\n- \"WARZYWA\" (position 25, single-word ALL_CAPS)\n- Various body text joins\n\nThe bilingual suppression correctly fires (position-0 mixed-case + position-1 ALL_CAPS with semantic similarity > 0.4). \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" is suppressed from threshold computation. \"Faszerowana papryka\" wins.\n\n---\n\n## Fix 2: Pre-dedup Sub-section Header Removal\n\n### Root cause\n\nThe dedup rule at line 489 unconditionally prefers shorter candidates when one is a substring of another. This is correct for most cases (e.g., \"Pierogi Ruskie\" over \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\") but destructive when a short **sub-section header** shares words with the actual title.\n\nIn the CHLEBEK case: \"CHLEBEK\" (position 8) is a sub-section header for the bread portion of the recipe. It is a substring of the actual title \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (position 1). The dedup rule removes the real title.\n\nThe existing prefix filter at line 440 was designed to handle this, but it only removes prefixes of `firstStructuralHeading`. When `bestStructural` resolves to \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" instead of the real title (due to cross-lingual embedding noise), the prefix filter targets the wrong heading and \"CHLEBEK\" survives.\n\n### Specific changes\n\nAdd a pre-dedup filter between the continuation join protection (line 482) and the dedup (line 489). The filter identifies **sub-section headers**: ALL_CAPS candidates that are followed in the source document by ingredient-like content.\n\n**Insert after line 482, before the dedup block:**\n\n```typescript\n// Pre-dedup: remove sub-section headers that are substrings of other surviving candidates.\n// A sub-section header is an ALL_CAPS candidate followed by ingredient-like lines in the source.\n// Example: \"CHLEBEK\" (bread section header, followed by \"500 g mąki\") is a substring of\n// \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (the real title). Without this filter, dedup kills the title.\nselected = selected.filter((candidate) => {\n  if (!isAllCaps(candidate.text)) return true;\n  // Check if this candidate is followed by ingredient-like content\n  const nextSourceLines = lines.slice(candidate.position + 1, candidate.position + 3);\n  const followedByIngredients = nextSourceLines.some(\n    (l) => looksLikeIngredient(l.trim()) || /^\\s*\\d/.test(l.trim())\n  );\n  if (!followedByIngredients) return true;\n  // Only remove if a longer candidate contains this one as a substring\n  const candidateLower = candidate.text.toLowerCase();\n  const hasLongerParent = selected.some(\n    (other) =>\n      other !== candidate &&\n      other.text.length > candidate.text.length &&\n      other.text.toLowerCase().includes(candidateLower)\n  );\n  return !hasLongerParent;\n});\n```\n\n### Why this is safe\n\nThe filter requires **three conditions** to fire simultaneously:\n1. The candidate is ALL_CAPS\n2. It is followed by ingredient-like lines (strong sub-section signal)\n3. A longer candidate containing it as a substring also survived threshold\n\nThis is conservative — it only resolves the specific conflict where a sub-section header's name overlaps with the title. It cannot remove standalone titles because condition (3) requires a longer superset candidate to exist.\n\n### Regression analysis\n\n| Test case | Effect |\n|---|---|\n| ARAYES SHRAK | \"ARAYES\" (1 word) doesn't survive threshold independently — never reaches dedup. No change. |\n| Baked Eggs | No ALL_CAPS sub-section headers that are substrings of the title. No change. |\n| CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM | **\"CHLEBEK\" removed** — followed by \"500 g mąki\" (ingredient) and is substring of real title. Fix applied. |\n| Finnish Flatbreads | Two separate recipe titles, neither is a substring of the other. No change. |\n| Faszerowana papryka | Already fixed by Fix 1 (NA 3 PAPRYKI filtered). No sub-section header conflict. No change. |\n| MIXED SEED CRISPBREAD | No sub-section header conflicts. No change. |\n| OVERNIGHT STRAIGHT PIZZA DOUGH | No sub-section header conflicts. No change. |\n| SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS | No sub-section header conflicts. No change. |\n| Kimchi z ogórków | \"SKŁADNIKI\" is ALL_CAPS and followed by ingredients, but no longer candidate contains \"SKŁADNIKI\". Condition (3) fails. No change. |\n| MŁODE PORY DUSZONE W PIWIE | No ALL_CAPS sub-section headers that are substrings of the title. No change. |\n\n### Expected impact on Failure 1\n\nWith Fix 1 removing \"DLA 4 OSÓB\", \"PRZYGOTOWANIE 1 GODZ. 45 MIN\", \"GOTOWANIE 30 MIN\", and \"OCZEKIWANIE 1 GODZ. 30 MIN\" from the candidate pool, the remaining ALL_CAPS candidates are:\n- \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (position 1)\n- \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" (position 2)\n- \"CHLEBEK\" (position 8)\n\nFix 1 alone helps by reducing noise, but the core CHLEBEK/dedup issue persists. Fix 2 then removes \"CHLEBEK\" because:\n- It's ALL_CAPS ✓\n- Followed by \"500 g mąki\" (ingredient) ✓\n- \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" contains \"CHLEBEK\" and is longer ✓\n\nSimilarly, \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" at position 2 is followed by \"500 g strączków zielonego groszku\" (ingredient) and is a substring of \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" — wait, no. Is \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" a substring of \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"? \"warzywa i boczek\" vs \"chlebek z warzywami i boczkiem\" — no, \"warzywami\" ≠ \"warzywa\". So condition (3) fails for \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\". It survives.\n\nFinal candidates after Fix 2: \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" and \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\". The multi-title guard (line 504) fires with 2 ALL_CAPS candidates. `isSubHeader` checks if \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" (the non-first) is followed by ingredients → yes → `isSubHeader = true` → collapses to `[sortedCaps[0]]` = \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (position 1 < position 2).\n\nResult: **\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"** — correct.\n\n---\n\n## Fix 3: Structural Heading Selection Robustness (Optional)\n\n### Root cause\n\n`bestStructural` is chosen purely by `rawScore`, which depends on MiniLM cross-lingual embedding quality. For Polish text, the model may not reliably rank a 5-word compound title above a 3-word food phrase. This makes the downstream prefix filter fragile.\n\n### Specific changes\n\nAdd a tiebreaker to `bestStructural` selection: when rawScores are within 0.03 of each other, prefer the candidate with more words (longer title = more specific = more likely the actual title, not a section header). If word counts are also equal, prefer the earlier position.\n\n**Before:**\n```typescript\nconst bestStructural = structuralCandidates.length > 0\n  ? structuralCandidates.reduce((a, b) => a.rawScore > b.rawScore ? a : b)\n  : null;\n```\n\n**After:**\n```typescript\nconst bestStructural = structuralCandidates.length > 0\n  ? structuralCandidates.reduce((a, b) => {\n      const scoreDiff = a.rawScore - b.rawScore;\n      if (Math.abs(scoreDiff) > 0.03) return scoreDiff > 0 ? a : b;\n      // Tiebreak: more words (more specific) → better\n      const wcDiff = wordCount(b.text) - wordCount(a.text);\n      if (wcDiff !== 0) return wcDiff > 0 ? b : a;\n      // Tiebreak: earlier position → better\n      return a.position < b.position ? a : b;\n    })\n  : null;\n```\n\nThis makes the prefix filter at line 440 more likely to target the correct (longer, more specific) heading, providing defense-in-depth alongside Fix 2. With a 0.03 threshold, a clearly better rawScore still wins.\n\n### Risk assessment\n\nLow risk. Only changes behavior when two structural headings have nearly identical rawScores (within 0.03). In that case, preferring the longer/earlier candidate is almost always correct — a sub-section header is never the title when a longer heading containing the same topic exists.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n| Fix | Addresses | Mechanism | Risk |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Fix 1**: Polish metadata patterns | Failure 2 directly; reduces Failure 1 noise | Hard filter in `looksLikeMetadata` | Very low — patterns are specific and well-attested |\n| **Fix 2**: Pre-dedup sub-section removal | Failure 1 directly | Pre-dedup filter gated on 3 conditions | Low — conservative triple-condition gate |\n| **Fix 3**: Structural heading tiebreaker | Failure 1 (defense-in-depth) | Tiebreaker with 0.03 threshold | Very low — only changes close-call decisions |\n\n### Expected accuracy after fixes\n\nAll 8 existing test cases should pass. The 2 new test cases (Kimchi z ogórków, MŁODE PORY DUSZONE W PIWIE) should also benefit from the Polish metadata patterns.\n","numLines":234,"startLine":1,"totalLines":234}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GjnpjJ4yq8drPCwXzvGgSU","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/**\n     2→ * Title Extraction\n     3→ * Extracts potential recipe title from OCR text using heuristics or semantic embeddings\n     4→ */\n     5→\n     6→import { cosineSimilarity } from \"./embeddings\";\n     7→\n     8→export type EmbedFn = (text: string) => Promise<Array<number>>;\n     9→\n    10→const TITLE_REFERENCE =\n    11→  \"recipe name, dish title, name of the food, nazwa przepisu, nazwa dania\";\n    12→const HEADER_REFERENCE =\n    13→  \"ingredients list, cooking directions, section heading, składniki, przygotowanie, sposób wykonania\";\n    14→const NOISE_REFERENCE =\n    15→  \"page number, table of contents, book footer, garbled text\";\n    16→\n    17→/**\n    18→ * Measurement units commonly found in ingredient lists\n    19→ */\n    20→const MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS = [\n    21→  \"cup\",\n    22→  \"cups\",\n    23→  \"tbsp\",\n    24→  \"tsp\",\n    25→  \"tablespoon\",\n    26→  \"teaspoon\",\n    27→  \"oz\",\n    28→  \"lb\",\n    29→  \"gram\",\n    30→  \"grams\",\n    31→  \"kg\",\n    32→  \"ml\",\n    33→  \"liter\",\n    34→  \"pinch\",\n    35→  \"dash\",\n    36→  \"handful\",\n    37→];\n    38→\n    39→/**\n    40→ * Patterns that identify recipe metadata lines (not titles)\n    41→ */\n    42→const METADATA_PATTERNS = [\n    43→  /^(SERVES?|MAKES?|YIELDS?)\\b/i,\n    44→  /^(PREP(ARATION)?|COOK(ING)?|PROOF|RISING|FERMENTATION|REST(ING)?)\\s*(AND\\s*)?(COOK(ING)?)?\\s*TIME/i,\n    45→  /^SAMPLE\\s+SCHEDULE\\b/i,\n    46→  /^BULK\\s+FERMENTATION\\b/i,\n    47→  /^(THIS\\s+RECIPE\\s+)?MAKES\\b/i,\n    48→];\n    49→\n    50→/**\n    51→ * Single-word non-title words — standalone OCR fragments unlikely to be recipe titles\n    52→ */\n    53→const NON_TITLE_WORDS = new Set([\n    54→  \"the\", \"and\", \"for\", \"but\", \"not\", \"you\", \"all\", \"can\", \"are\", \"was\",\n    55→  \"has\", \"his\", \"her\", \"its\", \"our\", \"who\", \"how\", \"may\", \"new\", \"now\",\n    56→  \"old\", \"see\", \"way\", \"did\", \"get\", \"let\", \"say\", \"she\", \"too\", \"use\",\n    57→  \"buns\", \"with\",\n    58→]);\n    59→\n    60→function looksLikeIngredient(line: string): boolean {\n    61→  const lowerLine = line.toLowerCase();\n    62→  return MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => lowerLine.includes(pattern));\n    63→}\n    64→\n    65→function startsWithNumber(line: string): boolean {\n    66→  return /^\\s*\\d/.test(line);\n    67→}\n    68→\n    69→function isAllCaps(line: string): boolean {\n    70→  const letters = line.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\");\n    71→  return letters.length > 0 && letters === letters.toUpperCase();\n    72→}\n    73→\n    74→function looksLikeMetadata(text: string): boolean {\n    75→  return METADATA_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => pattern.test(text.trim()));\n    76→}\n    77→\n    78→function isLikelyGarbled(text: string): boolean {\n    79→  const letters = text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\");\n    80→  if (letters.length < 2) return true;\n    81→\n    82→  // Check vowel ratio — English/Polish text typically has 30–50% vowels\n    83→  const vowels = letters.replace(/[^aeiouAEIOUyYąęóĄĘÓ]/g, \"\").length;\n    84→  const vowelRatio = vowels / letters.length;\n    85→  if (vowelRatio < 0.15 || vowelRatio > 0.85) return true;\n    86→\n    87→  // Single orphaned word ≤3 letters that isn't a common word\n    88→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n    89→  const COMMON_SHORT = new Set([\n    90→    \"the\", \"and\", \"for\", \"but\", \"not\", \"you\", \"all\", \"can\", \"had\", \"her\",\n    91→    \"was\", \"one\", \"our\", \"out\", \"are\", \"has\", \"his\", \"how\", \"its\", \"may\",\n    92→    \"new\", \"now\", \"old\", \"see\", \"way\", \"who\", \"did\", \"get\", \"let\", \"say\",\n    93→    \"she\", \"too\", \"use\",\n    94→  ]);\n    95→  if (words.length === 1 && letters.length <= 3 && !COMMON_SHORT.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) {\n    96→    return true;\n    97→  }\n    98→\n    99→  // Recipe titles never start with a lowercase letter\n   100→  if (/^[a-z]/.test(text.trim())) {\n   101→    return true;\n   102→  }\n   103→\n   104→  // Mid-text sentence boundary (\". \" followed by a letter) — body text fragment spliced from multiple sentences\n   105→  const trimmed = text.trim();\n   106→  if (/\\.\\s+[a-zA-Z]/.test(trimmed) && !trimmed.endsWith(\")\")) {\n   107→    return true;\n   108→  }\n   109→\n   110→  // Multi-word candidate containing a garbled OCR fragment: a short lowercase word that isn't a known short word\n   111→  if (words.length >= 2) {\n   112→    const commonShort2 = new Set([\n   113→      \"a\", \"i\", \"of\", \"or\", \"to\", \"in\", \"on\", \"is\", \"it\", \"an\",\n   114→      \"as\", \"at\", \"by\", \"do\", \"go\", \"if\", \"no\", \"so\", \"up\", \"we\",\n   115→      \"w\", \"z\",  // Polish prepositions\n   116→    ]);\n   117→    const hasGarbledWord = words.some(\n   118→      (w) =>\n   119→        /^[a-z]/.test(w) &&\n   120→        w.replace(/[^a-z]/g, \"\").length <= 2 &&\n   121→        !commonShort2.has(w.toLowerCase())\n   122→    );\n   123→    if (hasGarbledWord) {\n   124→      return true;\n   125→    }\n   126→  }\n   127→\n   128→  return false;\n   129→}\n   130→\n   131→function passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n   132→  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n   133→  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n   134→  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n   135→  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n   136→  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n   137→  // Single-word non-title fragments\n   138→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n   139→  if (words.length === 1 && NON_TITLE_WORDS.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) return false;\n   140→  return true;\n   141→}\n   142→\n   143→/**\n   144→ * Detect initial burst of short garbled lines.\n   145→ * Returns the index of the first non-garbled or long line.\n   146→ */\n   147→function findBurstEnd(lines: Array<{ text: string }>): number {\n   148→  let i = 0;\n   149→  while (i < lines.length && lines[i].text.length < 20 && isLikelyGarbled(lines[i].text)) {\n   150→    i++;\n   151→  }\n   152→  return i;\n   153→}\n   154→\n   155→function wordCount(text: string): number {\n   156→  return text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.length > 0).length;\n   157→}\n   158→\n   159→/**\n   160→ * Build candidate strings from lines: single lines plus multi-line joins (2-3 consecutive).\n   161→ * Skips initial burst of short garbled lines. Scans all remaining lines. Caps at 25.\n   162→ */\n   163→export type CandidateOrigin = \"single\" | \"2-line\" | \"3-line\";\n   164→\n   165→function buildCandidates(\n   166→  lines: Array<string>\n   167→): Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin }> {\n   168→  const nonEmptyLines: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n   169→\n   170→  for (let i = 0; i < lines.length; i++) {\n   171→    const trimmed = lines[i].trim();\n   172→    if (trimmed.length > 0) {\n   173→      nonEmptyLines.push({ text: trimmed, index: i });\n   174→    }\n   175→  }\n   176→\n   177→  const burstEnd = findBurstEnd(nonEmptyLines);\n   178→\n   179→  // Pre-merge continuation lines: a line starting with /&+:( is never a standalone title.\n   180→  // Merge it into the preceding line so the complete title enters the pool as a single candidate,\n   181→  // avoiding the fragile chain of conditions required by the downstream join survival logic.\n   182→  // Limitation: only one continuation line per preceding line is merged. Titles split across\n   183→  // three or more lines with continuation tokens (rare in practice) are not handled here —\n   184→  // the downstream 2-line and 3-line join candidates cover those cases instead.\n   185→  const mergedLines: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n   186→  for (let i = burstEnd; i < nonEmptyLines.length; i++) {\n   187→    const line = nonEmptyLines[i];\n   188→    if (i + 1 < nonEmptyLines.length) {\n   189→      const nextText = nonEmptyLines[i + 1].text;\n   190→      if (/^[/&+:(]/.test(nextText)) {\n   191→        mergedLines.push({ text: `${line.text} ${nextText}`, index: line.index });\n   192→        i++;\n   193→        continue;\n   194→      }\n   195→    }\n   196→    mergedLines.push(line);\n   197→  }\n   198→\n   199→  const candidates: Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin }> = [];\n   200→  const seen = new Set<string>();\n   201→\n   202→  for (let i = 0; i < mergedLines.length; i++) {\n   203→    const line = mergedLines[i];\n   204→\n   205→    // Single line\n   206→    if (passesHardFilters(line.text)) {\n   207→      const norm = line.text.toLowerCase();\n   208→      if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n   209→        seen.add(norm);\n   210→        candidates.push({ text: line.text, position: line.index, origin: \"single\" });\n   211→      }\n   212→    }\n   213→\n   214→    // 2-line join\n   215→    if (i + 1 < mergedLines.length) {\n   216→      const joined2 = `${line.text} ${mergedLines[i + 1].text}`;\n   217→      if (passesHardFilters(joined2)) {\n   218→        const norm = joined2.toLowerCase();\n   219→        if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n   220→          seen.add(norm);\n   221→          candidates.push({ text: joined2, position: line.index, origin: \"2-line\" });\n   222→        }\n   223→      }\n   224→    }\n   225→\n   226→    // 3-line join\n   227→    if (i + 2 < mergedLines.length) {\n   228→      const joined3 = `${line.text} ${mergedLines[i + 1].text} ${mergedLines[i + 2].text}`;\n   229→      if (passesHardFilters(joined3)) {\n   230→        const norm = joined3.toLowerCase();\n   231→        if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n   232→          seen.add(norm);\n   233→          candidates.push({ text: joined3, position: line.index, origin: \"3-line\" });\n   234→        }\n   235→      }\n   236→    }\n   237→  }\n   238→\n   239→  // Pre-filter to 25 before embedding calls: prefer ALL_CAPS and short candidates.\n   240→  // Position-based scoring handles final ranking.\n   241→  if (candidates.length > 25) {\n   242→    const prioritized = candidates.slice().sort((a, b) => {\n   243→      const aAllCaps = isAllCaps(a.text) ? 0 : 1;\n   244→      const bAllCaps = isAllCaps(b.text) ? 0 : 1;\n   245→      if (aAllCaps !== bAllCaps) return aAllCaps - bAllCaps;\n   246→      const aShort = wordCount(a.text) <= 5 ? 0 : 1;\n   247→      const bShort = wordCount(b.text) <= 5 ? 0 : 1;\n   248→      return aShort - bShort;\n   249→    });\n   250→    return prioritized.slice(0, 25);\n   251→  }\n   252→\n   253→  return candidates;\n   254→}\n   255→\n   256→// Module-level cache for reference embeddings\n   257→let cachedTitleRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\n   258→let cachedHeaderRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\n   259→let cachedNoiseRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\n   260→\n   261→export function _resetEmbeddingCacheForTests(): void {\n   262→  cachedTitleRefEmbedding = null;\n   263→  cachedHeaderRefEmbedding = null;\n   264→  cachedNoiseRefEmbedding = null;\n   265→}\n   266→\n   267→export async function extractTitleWithEmbeddings(\n   268→  text: string,\n   269→  embed: EmbedFn\n   270→): Promise<string | undefined> {\n   271→  if (!text || text.trim().length === 0) {\n   272→    return undefined;\n   273→  }\n   274→\n   275→  const lines = text.split(\"\\n\");\n   276→  const candidates = buildCandidates(lines);\n   277→\n   278→  if (candidates.length === 0) {\n   279→    return undefined;\n   280→  }\n   281→\n   282→  // Cache reference embeddings\n   283→  if (!cachedTitleRefEmbedding) {\n   284→    cachedTitleRefEmbedding = await embed(TITLE_REFERENCE);\n   285→  }\n   286→  if (!cachedHeaderRefEmbedding) {\n   287→    cachedHeaderRefEmbedding = await embed(HEADER_REFERENCE);\n   288→  }\n   289→  if (!cachedNoiseRefEmbedding) {\n   290→    cachedNoiseRefEmbedding = await embed(NOISE_REFERENCE);\n   291→  }\n   292→\n   293→  // Find ALL_CAPS candidates with ≥2 words where every significant word has ≥4 alpha letters.\n   294→  // Insignificant tokens (≤1 alpha letter: \"/\", \"&\", \"+\", \":\", \"D)\", etc.) are filtered before\n   295→  // the check so that multi-line joins with continuation punctuation still qualify.\n   296→  const isStructuralHeading = (c: { text: string }): boolean => {\n   297→    if (!isAllCaps(c.text) || wordCount(c.text) < 2) return false;\n   298→    const sigWords = c.text.trim().split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length > 1);\n   299→    return sigWords.length >= 2 && sigWords.every((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n   300→  };\n   301→\n   302→  // Pass 1: compute rawScore for all candidates (embedding quality signal)\n   303→  const rawScored: Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin; rawScore: number; embedding: Array<number> }> = [];\n   304→  for (const candidate of candidates) {\n   305→    const embedding = await embed(candidate.text);\n   306→    const titleSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedTitleRefEmbedding);\n   307→    const headerSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedHeaderRefEmbedding);\n   308→    const noiseSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedNoiseRefEmbedding);\n   309→    const rawScore = titleSim - Math.max(headerSim, noiseSim);\n   310→    rawScored.push({ text: candidate.text, position: candidate.position, origin: candidate.origin, rawScore, embedding });\n   311→  }\n   312→\n   313→  // Select baseHeading by embedding quality (rawScore), not position.\n   314→  // This prevents OCR-garbled fragments from claiming the structural heading slot.\n   315→  const structuralCandidates = rawScored.filter((s) => isStructuralHeading(s));\n   316→\n   317→  // Penalize structural headings with truncated OCR words:\n   318→  // if \"FRON\" appears and another heading has \"SAFFRON\", \"FRON\" is likely garbled.\n   319→  for (const sc of structuralCandidates) {\n   320→    const sigWords = sc.text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n   321→    for (const other of structuralCandidates) {\n   322→      if (other === sc) continue;\n   323→      const otherSigWords = other.text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n   324→      const hasTruncation = sigWords.some((w) =>\n   325→        otherSigWords.some((ow) => ow !== w && ow.length > w.length && ow.endsWith(w))\n   326→      );\n   327→      if (hasTruncation) {\n   328→        sc.rawScore = -1.0;  // Hard disqualification — truncated OCR artifact\n   329→        break;\n   330→      }\n   331→    }\n   332→  }\n   333→\n   334→  const bestStructural = structuralCandidates.length > 0\n   335→    ? structuralCandidates.reduce((a, b) => a.rawScore > b.rawScore ? a : b)\n   336→    : null;\n   337→  const baseHeading = bestStructural ?? undefined;\n   338→\n   339→  // When the best structural heading has a continuation on the next line introduced by a\n   340→  // punctuation token (/, &, +, :, or parenthesis), prefer the longer 2-line join as the\n   341→  // complete heading. E.g. \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" + \"/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\".\n   342→  // Guard: the remainder after the prefix must start with a continuation character to avoid\n   343→  // merging two separate consecutive recipe titles (FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS stays separate\n   344→  // from FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS because \"FINNISH\" does not start with a continuation token).\n   345→  const firstStructuralHeading = baseHeading && (\n   346→    rawScored.find((c) => {\n   347→      if (!isStructuralHeading(c)) return false;\n   348→      const hLower = baseHeading.text.toLowerCase();\n   349→      const cLower = c.text.toLowerCase();\n   350→      return cLower.startsWith(hLower + \" \") && /^[/&+:(]/.test(cLower.slice(hLower.length + 1));\n   351→    }) ?? baseHeading\n   352→  );\n   353→\n   354→  // Pass 2: apply bonuses\n   355→  const scored: Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin; score: number; rawScore: number; baseScore: number; thresholdScore: number }> = rawScored.map((rs) => {\n   356→    // Position factor: multiplicative tiebreaker — amplifies existing signal, doesn't replace it\n   357→    const relativePosition = rs.position / lines.length;\n   358→    const positionFactor = relativePosition < 0.5\n   359→      ? 1.0 + 0.12 * (1 - relativePosition * 2)\n   360→      : 1.0;\n   361→\n   362→    // ALL_CAPS bonus: recipe books use ALL_CAPS for titles and section headings\n   363→    const allCapsBonus = isAllCaps(rs.text) && rs.text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4\n   364→      ? 0.08\n   365→      : 0;\n   366→\n   367→    // Structural heading bonus: best ALL_CAPS heading (or its continuation join) is almost always the recipe title\n   368→    const structuralBonus = firstStructuralHeading && rs.text === firstStructuralHeading.text ? 0.10 : 0;\n   369→\n   370→    // thresholdScore excludes structural bonus so the bonus doesn't inflate the threshold\n   371→    // and prevent equally-valid structural headings from passing on multi-recipe pages.\n   372→    const thresholdScore = rs.rawScore + allCapsBonus;\n   373→    // baseScore excludes position factor — used for diagnostics and ranking\n   374→    const baseScore = rs.rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n   375→    const score = rs.rawScore * positionFactor + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n   376→    return { text: rs.text, position: rs.position, origin: rs.origin, score, rawScore: rs.rawScore, baseScore, thresholdScore };\n   377→  });\n   378→\n   379→  if (scored.length === 0) {\n   380→    return undefined;\n   381→  }\n   382→\n   383→  // --- Pre-threshold bilingual title detection ---\n   384→  // When a mixed-case candidate at position 0 is followed by an ALL_CAPS candidate\n   385→  // at position ≤ 2 that is semantically similar to it, this is a bilingual recipe\n   386→  // page (e.g., Polish title + ALL_CAPS Korean romanization). Suppress confirmed\n   387→  // translation candidates before computing threshold so their bonuses don't inflate\n   388→  // the threshold beyond the mixed-case title's reach.\n   389→  // Note: we check position ≤ 2 (local proximity), not global ALL_CAPS count, so\n   390→  // section headers later in the document (SKŁADNIKI, WARZYWA, etc.) are irrelevant.\n   391→  let scoredForThreshold = scored;\n   392→  const prePos0 = scored.find((s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text));\n   393→  if (prePos0) {\n   394→    const nearbyAllCaps = scored.filter(\n   395→      (s) => isAllCaps(s.text) && s.position >= 1 && s.position <= 2\n   396→    );\n   397→    const pos0Embedding = rawScored.find((r) => r.text === prePos0.text)?.embedding;\n   398→    if (pos0Embedding && nearbyAllCaps.length > 0) {\n   399→      const translationCandidates = nearbyAllCaps.filter((cap) => {\n   400→        const capEmbedding = rawScored.find((r) => r.text === cap.text)?.embedding;\n   401→        if (!capEmbedding) return false;\n   402→        return cosineSimilarity(pos0Embedding, capEmbedding) > 0.4;\n   403→      });\n   404→      if (translationCandidates.length > 0) {\n   405→        // Also suppress multi-line joins that start with the translation text\n   406→        // (e.g. \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM Ingredients\" starts with \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\")\n   407→        scoredForThreshold = scored.filter((s) => {\n   408→          const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n   409→          return !translationCandidates.some((t) => sLower.startsWith(t.text.toLowerCase()));\n   410→        });\n   411→      }\n   412→    }\n   413→  }\n   414→\n   415→  // Use thresholdScore (excludes structural bonus) so the structural bonus doesn't inflate\n   416→  // the threshold and block equally-valid headings on multi-recipe pages.\n   417→  const bestThresholdScore = Math.max(...scoredForThreshold.map((s) => s.thresholdScore));\n   418→  const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7);\n   419→\n   420→  // Filter candidates above threshold\n   421→  let selected = scoredForThreshold.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n   422→\n   423→  // Empty-pool fallback: when threshold filtering discards every candidate,\n   424→  // the hard filters' structural verdict should not be overruled by weak\n   425→  // embedding differentiation. Return the best positional candidate.\n   426→  if (selected.length === 0 && scored.length > 0) {\n   427→    const fallback = scored\n   428→      .slice()\n   429→      .sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position || b.score - a.score);\n   430→    selected = [fallback[0]];\n   431→  }\n   432→\n   433→  // Remove word-boundary prefixes of firstStructuralHeading when the heading itself survived\n   434→  // the threshold. Cases:\n   435→  //   ARAYES case:  firstStructuralHeading = \"ARAYES SHRAK\" (2-word join qualifies; \"ARAYES\"\n   436→  //     alone = 1 word, so it never qualified). Filter removes \"ARAYES\" so dedup keeps the join.\n   437→  //   SAFFRON case: baseHeading was the partial line; continuation logic above upgraded\n   438→  //     firstStructuralHeading to the full join. Filter removes the partial so dedup keeps join.\n   439→  // Safety: only fires when the complete heading itself is in selected (passed the threshold).\n   440→  if (firstStructuralHeading && selected.some((s) => s.text === firstStructuralHeading.text)) {\n   441→    const fshLower = firstStructuralHeading.text.toLowerCase();\n   442→    selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n   443→      if (s.text === firstStructuralHeading.text) return true;\n   444→      const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n   445→      // Remove s if it is a space-delimited prefix of the structural heading\n   446→      return !fshLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \");\n   447→    });\n   448→  }\n   449→\n   450→  // Protect continuation joins: when a multi-line join (2-line or 3-line) survived the threshold\n   451→  // and its second part starts with a continuation character, remove the single-line prefix/suffix\n   452→  // so the dedup \"shorter wins\" rule doesn't destroy the complete join.\n   453→  // Note: the pre-merge step above already handles the common Baked Eggs case (&/continuation\n   454→  // on next line) by turning it into a single candidate — this block covers the rarer case where\n   455→  // a continuation-character join was generated as a 2-line/3-line candidate and the prefix\n   456→  // single also survived threshold independently (e.g. from a different code path or OCR layout).\n   457→  // Safety: only fires for joins whose continuation starts with /&+:( — digit continuations\n   458→  // like \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki\" are NOT protected, so dedup correctly keeps the shorter form.\n   459→  const survivingJoins = selected.filter((s) => s.origin === \"2-line\" || s.origin === \"3-line\");\n   460→  if (survivingJoins.length > 0) {\n   461→    selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n   462→      if (s.origin !== \"single\") return true;\n   463→      const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n   464→      // Remove PREFIX singles whose continuation join also survived\n   465→      const isPrefixOfJoin = survivingJoins.some((j) => {\n   466→        const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n   467→        if (!jLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \")) return false;\n   468→        const remainder = jLower.slice(sLower.length + 1);\n   469→        return /^[/&+:(]/.test(remainder);\n   470→      });\n   471→      if (isPrefixOfJoin) return false;\n   472→      // Remove SUFFIX singles (e.g. \"& Coriander\") whose parent join also survived\n   473→      const isSuffixOfJoin = survivingJoins.some((j) => {\n   474→        const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n   475→        if (!jLower.endsWith(\" \" + sLower)) return false;\n   476→        // Only remove if the suffix starts with a continuation character\n   477→        return /^[/&+:(]/.test(sLower);\n   478→      });\n   479→      if (isSuffixOfJoin) return false;\n   480→      return true;\n   481→    });\n   482→  }\n   483→\n   484→  // Deduplicate: if one title is a substring of another, keep the shorter (more focused) one.\n   485→  // DO NOT CHANGE THIS LOGIC — it has been incorrectly \"improved\" by the title-loop 5 times.\n   486→  // The tests require shorter wins: \"Pierogi Ruskie\" over \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\".\n   487→  // The pre-filter above handles the conflicting case (structural heading prefix removal) so that\n   488→  // the incomplete prefix line is never present here when the complete join is in selected.\n   489→  selected = selected.filter((a) => {\n   490→    const aLower = a.text.toLowerCase();\n   491→    return !selected.some(\n   492→      (b) =>\n   493→        b !== a &&\n   494→        aLower.includes(b.text.toLowerCase()) &&\n   495→        b.text.length < a.text.length\n   496→    );\n   497→  });\n   498→\n   499→  // Multi-title guard: only join multiple candidates with \"+\" when there is\n   500→  // structural evidence of a multi-recipe page (≥2 ALL_CAPS headings).\n   501→  // A single ALL_CAPS title among mixed-case survivors is a single-recipe page —\n   502→  // collapse to the highest-scoring candidate.\n   503→  // Zero ALL_CAPS survivors → mixed-case multi-title page → keep all.\n   504→  if (selected.length > 1) {\n   505→    const allCapsSelected = selected.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n   506→    if (allCapsSelected.length >= 2) {\n   507→      // Check whether non-first ALL_CAPS headings are section headers within one recipe\n   508→      // (followed immediately by ingredient-like content) rather than separate recipe titles.\n   509→      // A multi-recipe page has body text between titles; a single-recipe page has\n   510→      // ingredient lines immediately after each section heading.\n   511→      const sortedCaps = [...allCapsSelected].sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position);\n   512→      const isSubHeader = sortedCaps.slice(1).every((cap) => {\n   513→        const nextLines = lines.slice(cap.position + 1, cap.position + 3);\n   514→        return nextLines.some(\n   515→          (l) => looksLikeIngredient(l.trim()) || /^\\s*\\d/.test(l.trim())\n   516→        );\n   517→      });\n   518→      if (isSubHeader) {\n   519→        selected = [sortedCaps[0]];\n   520→      } else {\n   521→        selected = allCapsSelected;\n   522→      }\n   523→    } else if (allCapsSelected.length === 1) {\n   524→      selected = [selected.reduce((a, b) => (a.score > b.score ? a : b))];\n   525→    }\n   526→  }\n   527→\n   528→  // Cap at 3, sort by document position\n   529→  selected.sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position);\n   530→  selected = selected.slice(0, 3);\n   531→\n   532→  if (selected.length === 0) {\n   533→    return undefined;\n   534→  }\n   535→\n   536→  return selected.map((s) => s.text).join(\" + \");\n   537→}\n   538→\n   539→/**\n   540→ * Extract potential recipe title from OCR text (sync heuristic fallback)\n   541→ */\n   542→export function extractTitle(text: string): string | undefined {\n   543→  if (!text || text.trim().length === 0) {\n   544→    return undefined;\n   545→  }\n   546→\n   547→  const lines = text.split(\"\\n\").map((line) => line.trim());\n   548→\n   549→  for (const line of lines) {\n   550→    if (line.length === 0) continue;\n   551→    if (line.length < 3 || line.length > 50) continue;\n   552→    if (looksLikeIngredient(line)) continue;\n   553→    if (isAllCaps(line)) continue;\n   554→    if (startsWithNumber(line)) continue;\n   555→    return line;\n   556→  }\n   557→\n   558→  return undefined;\n   559→}\n   560→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"84856199-2e39-4e5f-88ee-7f061b951e03","uuid":"f0258ebd-3d23-42c4-8577-914b52c93598","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts","content":"/**\n * Title Extraction\n * Extracts potential recipe title from OCR text using heuristics or semantic embeddings\n */\n\nimport { cosineSimilarity } from \"./embeddings\";\n\nexport type EmbedFn = (text: string) => Promise<Array<number>>;\n\nconst TITLE_REFERENCE =\n  \"recipe name, dish title, name of the food, nazwa przepisu, nazwa dania\";\nconst HEADER_REFERENCE =\n  \"ingredients list, cooking directions, section heading, składniki, przygotowanie, sposób wykonania\";\nconst NOISE_REFERENCE =\n  \"page number, table of contents, book footer, garbled text\";\n\n/**\n * Measurement units commonly found in ingredient lists\n */\nconst MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS = [\n  \"cup\",\n  \"cups\",\n  \"tbsp\",\n  \"tsp\",\n  \"tablespoon\",\n  \"teaspoon\",\n  \"oz\",\n  \"lb\",\n  \"gram\",\n  \"grams\",\n  \"kg\",\n  \"ml\",\n  \"liter\",\n  \"pinch\",\n  \"dash\",\n  \"handful\",\n];\n\n/**\n * Patterns that identify recipe metadata lines (not titles)\n */\nconst METADATA_PATTERNS = [\n  /^(SERVES?|MAKES?|YIELDS?)\\b/i,\n  /^(PREP(ARATION)?|COOK(ING)?|PROOF|RISING|FERMENTATION|REST(ING)?)\\s*(AND\\s*)?(COOK(ING)?)?\\s*TIME/i,\n  /^SAMPLE\\s+SCHEDULE\\b/i,\n  /^BULK\\s+FERMENTATION\\b/i,\n  /^(THIS\\s+RECIPE\\s+)?MAKES\\b/i,\n];\n\n/**\n * Single-word non-title words — standalone OCR fragments unlikely to be recipe titles\n */\nconst NON_TITLE_WORDS = new Set([\n  \"the\", \"and\", \"for\", \"but\", \"not\", \"you\", \"all\", \"can\", \"are\", \"was\",\n  \"has\", \"his\", \"her\", \"its\", \"our\", \"who\", \"how\", \"may\", \"new\", \"now\",\n  \"old\", \"see\", \"way\", \"did\", \"get\", \"let\", \"say\", \"she\", \"too\", \"use\",\n  \"buns\", \"with\",\n]);\n\nfunction looksLikeIngredient(line: string): boolean {\n  const lowerLine = line.toLowerCase();\n  return MEASUREMENT_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => lowerLine.includes(pattern));\n}\n\nfunction startsWithNumber(line: string): boolean {\n  return /^\\s*\\d/.test(line);\n}\n\nfunction isAllCaps(line: string): boolean {\n  const letters = line.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\");\n  return letters.length > 0 && letters === letters.toUpperCase();\n}\n\nfunction looksLikeMetadata(text: string): boolean {\n  return METADATA_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => pattern.test(text.trim()));\n}\n\nfunction isLikelyGarbled(text: string): boolean {\n  const letters = text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\");\n  if (letters.length < 2) return true;\n\n  // Check vowel ratio — English/Polish text typically has 30–50% vowels\n  const vowels = letters.replace(/[^aeiouAEIOUyYąęóĄĘÓ]/g, \"\").length;\n  const vowelRatio = vowels / letters.length;\n  if (vowelRatio < 0.15 || vowelRatio > 0.85) return true;\n\n  // Single orphaned word ≤3 letters that isn't a common word\n  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n  const COMMON_SHORT = new Set([\n    \"the\", \"and\", \"for\", \"but\", \"not\", \"you\", \"all\", \"can\", \"had\", \"her\",\n    \"was\", \"one\", \"our\", \"out\", \"are\", \"has\", \"his\", \"how\", \"its\", \"may\",\n    \"new\", \"now\", \"old\", \"see\", \"way\", \"who\", \"did\", \"get\", \"let\", \"say\",\n    \"she\", \"too\", \"use\",\n  ]);\n  if (words.length === 1 && letters.length <= 3 && !COMMON_SHORT.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) {\n    return true;\n  }\n\n  // Recipe titles never start with a lowercase letter\n  if (/^[a-z]/.test(text.trim())) {\n    return true;\n  }\n\n  // Mid-text sentence boundary (\". \" followed by a letter) — body text fragment spliced from multiple sentences\n  const trimmed = text.trim();\n  if (/\\.\\s+[a-zA-Z]/.test(trimmed) && !trimmed.endsWith(\")\")) {\n    return true;\n  }\n\n  // Multi-word candidate containing a garbled OCR fragment: a short lowercase word that isn't a known short word\n  if (words.length >= 2) {\n    const commonShort2 = new Set([\n      \"a\", \"i\", \"of\", \"or\", \"to\", \"in\", \"on\", \"is\", \"it\", \"an\",\n      \"as\", \"at\", \"by\", \"do\", \"go\", \"if\", \"no\", \"so\", \"up\", \"we\",\n      \"w\", \"z\",  // Polish prepositions\n    ]);\n    const hasGarbledWord = words.some(\n      (w) =>\n        /^[a-z]/.test(w) &&\n        w.replace(/[^a-z]/g, \"\").length <= 2 &&\n        !commonShort2.has(w.toLowerCase())\n    );\n    if (hasGarbledWord) {\n      return true;\n    }\n  }\n\n  return false;\n}\n\nfunction passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n  // Single-word non-title fragments\n  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n  if (words.length === 1 && NON_TITLE_WORDS.has(text.trim().toLowerCase())) return false;\n  return true;\n}\n\n/**\n * Detect initial burst of short garbled lines.\n * Returns the index of the first non-garbled or long line.\n */\nfunction findBurstEnd(lines: Array<{ text: string }>): number {\n  let i = 0;\n  while (i < lines.length && lines[i].text.length < 20 && isLikelyGarbled(lines[i].text)) {\n    i++;\n  }\n  return i;\n}\n\nfunction wordCount(text: string): number {\n  return text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.length > 0).length;\n}\n\n/**\n * Build candidate strings from lines: single lines plus multi-line joins (2-3 consecutive).\n * Skips initial burst of short garbled lines. Scans all remaining lines. Caps at 25.\n */\nexport type CandidateOrigin = \"single\" | \"2-line\" | \"3-line\";\n\nfunction buildCandidates(\n  lines: Array<string>\n): Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin }> {\n  const nonEmptyLines: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n\n  for (let i = 0; i < lines.length; i++) {\n    const trimmed = lines[i].trim();\n    if (trimmed.length > 0) {\n      nonEmptyLines.push({ text: trimmed, index: i });\n    }\n  }\n\n  const burstEnd = findBurstEnd(nonEmptyLines);\n\n  // Pre-merge continuation lines: a line starting with /&+:( is never a standalone title.\n  // Merge it into the preceding line so the complete title enters the pool as a single candidate,\n  // avoiding the fragile chain of conditions required by the downstream join survival logic.\n  // Limitation: only one continuation line per preceding line is merged. Titles split across\n  // three or more lines with continuation tokens (rare in practice) are not handled here —\n  // the downstream 2-line and 3-line join candidates cover those cases instead.\n  const mergedLines: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n  for (let i = burstEnd; i < nonEmptyLines.length; i++) {\n    const line = nonEmptyLines[i];\n    if (i + 1 < nonEmptyLines.length) {\n      const nextText = nonEmptyLines[i + 1].text;\n      if (/^[/&+:(]/.test(nextText)) {\n        mergedLines.push({ text: `${line.text} ${nextText}`, index: line.index });\n        i++;\n        continue;\n      }\n    }\n    mergedLines.push(line);\n  }\n\n  const candidates: Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin }> = [];\n  const seen = new Set<string>();\n\n  for (let i = 0; i < mergedLines.length; i++) {\n    const line = mergedLines[i];\n\n    // Single line\n    if (passesHardFilters(line.text)) {\n      const norm = line.text.toLowerCase();\n      if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n        seen.add(norm);\n        candidates.push({ text: line.text, position: line.index, origin: \"single\" });\n      }\n    }\n\n    // 2-line join\n    if (i + 1 < mergedLines.length) {\n      const joined2 = `${line.text} ${mergedLines[i + 1].text}`;\n      if (passesHardFilters(joined2)) {\n        const norm = joined2.toLowerCase();\n        if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n          seen.add(norm);\n          candidates.push({ text: joined2, position: line.index, origin: \"2-line\" });\n        }\n      }\n    }\n\n    // 3-line join\n    if (i + 2 < mergedLines.length) {\n      const joined3 = `${line.text} ${mergedLines[i + 1].text} ${mergedLines[i + 2].text}`;\n      if (passesHardFilters(joined3)) {\n        const norm = joined3.toLowerCase();\n        if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n          seen.add(norm);\n          candidates.push({ text: joined3, position: line.index, origin: \"3-line\" });\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Pre-filter to 25 before embedding calls: prefer ALL_CAPS and short candidates.\n  // Position-based scoring handles final ranking.\n  if (candidates.length > 25) {\n    const prioritized = candidates.slice().sort((a, b) => {\n      const aAllCaps = isAllCaps(a.text) ? 0 : 1;\n      const bAllCaps = isAllCaps(b.text) ? 0 : 1;\n      if (aAllCaps !== bAllCaps) return aAllCaps - bAllCaps;\n      const aShort = wordCount(a.text) <= 5 ? 0 : 1;\n      const bShort = wordCount(b.text) <= 5 ? 0 : 1;\n      return aShort - bShort;\n    });\n    return prioritized.slice(0, 25);\n  }\n\n  return candidates;\n}\n\n// Module-level cache for reference embeddings\nlet cachedTitleRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\nlet cachedHeaderRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\nlet cachedNoiseRefEmbedding: Array<number> | null = null;\n\nexport function _resetEmbeddingCacheForTests(): void {\n  cachedTitleRefEmbedding = null;\n  cachedHeaderRefEmbedding = null;\n  cachedNoiseRefEmbedding = null;\n}\n\nexport async function extractTitleWithEmbeddings(\n  text: string,\n  embed: EmbedFn\n): Promise<string | undefined> {\n  if (!text || text.trim().length === 0) {\n    return undefined;\n  }\n\n  const lines = text.split(\"\\n\");\n  const candidates = buildCandidates(lines);\n\n  if (candidates.length === 0) {\n    return undefined;\n  }\n\n  // Cache reference embeddings\n  if (!cachedTitleRefEmbedding) {\n    cachedTitleRefEmbedding = await embed(TITLE_REFERENCE);\n  }\n  if (!cachedHeaderRefEmbedding) {\n    cachedHeaderRefEmbedding = await embed(HEADER_REFERENCE);\n  }\n  if (!cachedNoiseRefEmbedding) {\n    cachedNoiseRefEmbedding = await embed(NOISE_REFERENCE);\n  }\n\n  // Find ALL_CAPS candidates with ≥2 words where every significant word has ≥4 alpha letters.\n  // Insignificant tokens (≤1 alpha letter: \"/\", \"&\", \"+\", \":\", \"D)\", etc.) are filtered before\n  // the check so that multi-line joins with continuation punctuation still qualify.\n  const isStructuralHeading = (c: { text: string }): boolean => {\n    if (!isAllCaps(c.text) || wordCount(c.text) < 2) return false;\n    const sigWords = c.text.trim().split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length > 1);\n    return sigWords.length >= 2 && sigWords.every((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n  };\n\n  // Pass 1: compute rawScore for all candidates (embedding quality signal)\n  const rawScored: Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin; rawScore: number; embedding: Array<number> }> = [];\n  for (const candidate of candidates) {\n    const embedding = await embed(candidate.text);\n    const titleSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedTitleRefEmbedding);\n    const headerSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedHeaderRefEmbedding);\n    const noiseSim = cosineSimilarity(embedding, cachedNoiseRefEmbedding);\n    const rawScore = titleSim - Math.max(headerSim, noiseSim);\n    rawScored.push({ text: candidate.text, position: candidate.position, origin: candidate.origin, rawScore, embedding });\n  }\n\n  // Select baseHeading by embedding quality (rawScore), not position.\n  // This prevents OCR-garbled fragments from claiming the structural heading slot.\n  const structuralCandidates = rawScored.filter((s) => isStructuralHeading(s));\n\n  // Penalize structural headings with truncated OCR words:\n  // if \"FRON\" appears and another heading has \"SAFFRON\", \"FRON\" is likely garbled.\n  for (const sc of structuralCandidates) {\n    const sigWords = sc.text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n    for (const other of structuralCandidates) {\n      if (other === sc) continue;\n      const otherSigWords = other.text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n      const hasTruncation = sigWords.some((w) =>\n        otherSigWords.some((ow) => ow !== w && ow.length > w.length && ow.endsWith(w))\n      );\n      if (hasTruncation) {\n        sc.rawScore = -1.0;  // Hard disqualification — truncated OCR artifact\n        break;\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  const bestStructural = structuralCandidates.length > 0\n    ? structuralCandidates.reduce((a, b) => a.rawScore > b.rawScore ? a : b)\n    : null;\n  const baseHeading = bestStructural ?? undefined;\n\n  // When the best structural heading has a continuation on the next line introduced by a\n  // punctuation token (/, &, +, :, or parenthesis), prefer the longer 2-line join as the\n  // complete heading. E.g. \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" + \"/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\".\n  // Guard: the remainder after the prefix must start with a continuation character to avoid\n  // merging two separate consecutive recipe titles (FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS stays separate\n  // from FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS because \"FINNISH\" does not start with a continuation token).\n  const firstStructuralHeading = baseHeading && (\n    rawScored.find((c) => {\n      if (!isStructuralHeading(c)) return false;\n      const hLower = baseHeading.text.toLowerCase();\n      const cLower = c.text.toLowerCase();\n      return cLower.startsWith(hLower + \" \") && /^[/&+:(]/.test(cLower.slice(hLower.length + 1));\n    }) ?? baseHeading\n  );\n\n  // Pass 2: apply bonuses\n  const scored: Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin; score: number; rawScore: number; baseScore: number; thresholdScore: number }> = rawScored.map((rs) => {\n    // Position factor: multiplicative tiebreaker — amplifies existing signal, doesn't replace it\n    const relativePosition = rs.position / lines.length;\n    const positionFactor = relativePosition < 0.5\n      ? 1.0 + 0.12 * (1 - relativePosition * 2)\n      : 1.0;\n\n    // ALL_CAPS bonus: recipe books use ALL_CAPS for titles and section headings\n    const allCapsBonus = isAllCaps(rs.text) && rs.text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4\n      ? 0.08\n      : 0;\n\n    // Structural heading bonus: best ALL_CAPS heading (or its continuation join) is almost always the recipe title\n    const structuralBonus = firstStructuralHeading && rs.text === firstStructuralHeading.text ? 0.10 : 0;\n\n    // thresholdScore excludes structural bonus so the bonus doesn't inflate the threshold\n    // and prevent equally-valid structural headings from passing on multi-recipe pages.\n    const thresholdScore = rs.rawScore + allCapsBonus;\n    // baseScore excludes position factor — used for diagnostics and ranking\n    const baseScore = rs.rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n    const score = rs.rawScore * positionFactor + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n    return { text: rs.text, position: rs.position, origin: rs.origin, score, rawScore: rs.rawScore, baseScore, thresholdScore };\n  });\n\n  if (scored.length === 0) {\n    return undefined;\n  }\n\n  // --- Pre-threshold bilingual title detection ---\n  // When a mixed-case candidate at position 0 is followed by an ALL_CAPS candidate\n  // at position ≤ 2 that is semantically similar to it, this is a bilingual recipe\n  // page (e.g., Polish title + ALL_CAPS Korean romanization). Suppress confirmed\n  // translation candidates before computing threshold so their bonuses don't inflate\n  // the threshold beyond the mixed-case title's reach.\n  // Note: we check position ≤ 2 (local proximity), not global ALL_CAPS count, so\n  // section headers later in the document (SKŁADNIKI, WARZYWA, etc.) are irrelevant.\n  let scoredForThreshold = scored;\n  const prePos0 = scored.find((s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text));\n  if (prePos0) {\n    const nearbyAllCaps = scored.filter(\n      (s) => isAllCaps(s.text) && s.position >= 1 && s.position <= 2\n    );\n    const pos0Embedding = rawScored.find((r) => r.text === prePos0.text)?.embedding;\n    if (pos0Embedding && nearbyAllCaps.length > 0) {\n      const translationCandidates = nearbyAllCaps.filter((cap) => {\n        const capEmbedding = rawScored.find((r) => r.text === cap.text)?.embedding;\n        if (!capEmbedding) return false;\n        return cosineSimilarity(pos0Embedding, capEmbedding) > 0.4;\n      });\n      if (translationCandidates.length > 0) {\n        // Also suppress multi-line joins that start with the translation text\n        // (e.g. \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM Ingredients\" starts with \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\")\n        scoredForThreshold = scored.filter((s) => {\n          const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n          return !translationCandidates.some((t) => sLower.startsWith(t.text.toLowerCase()));\n        });\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Use thresholdScore (excludes structural bonus) so the structural bonus doesn't inflate\n  // the threshold and block equally-valid headings on multi-recipe pages.\n  const bestThresholdScore = Math.max(...scoredForThreshold.map((s) => s.thresholdScore));\n  const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7);\n\n  // Filter candidates above threshold\n  let selected = scoredForThreshold.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n\n  // Empty-pool fallback: when threshold filtering discards every candidate,\n  // the hard filters' structural verdict should not be overruled by weak\n  // embedding differentiation. Return the best positional candidate.\n  if (selected.length === 0 && scored.length > 0) {\n    const fallback = scored\n      .slice()\n      .sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position || b.score - a.score);\n    selected = [fallback[0]];\n  }\n\n  // Remove word-boundary prefixes of firstStructuralHeading when the heading itself survived\n  // the threshold. Cases:\n  //   ARAYES case:  firstStructuralHeading = \"ARAYES SHRAK\" (2-word join qualifies; \"ARAYES\"\n  //     alone = 1 word, so it never qualified). Filter removes \"ARAYES\" so dedup keeps the join.\n  //   SAFFRON case: baseHeading was the partial line; continuation logic above upgraded\n  //     firstStructuralHeading to the full join. Filter removes the partial so dedup keeps join.\n  // Safety: only fires when the complete heading itself is in selected (passed the threshold).\n  if (firstStructuralHeading && selected.some((s) => s.text === firstStructuralHeading.text)) {\n    const fshLower = firstStructuralHeading.text.toLowerCase();\n    selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n      if (s.text === firstStructuralHeading.text) return true;\n      const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n      // Remove s if it is a space-delimited prefix of the structural heading\n      return !fshLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \");\n    });\n  }\n\n  // Protect continuation joins: when a multi-line join (2-line or 3-line) survived the threshold\n  // and its second part starts with a continuation character, remove the single-line prefix/suffix\n  // so the dedup \"shorter wins\" rule doesn't destroy the complete join.\n  // Note: the pre-merge step above already handles the common Baked Eggs case (&/continuation\n  // on next line) by turning it into a single candidate — this block covers the rarer case where\n  // a continuation-character join was generated as a 2-line/3-line candidate and the prefix\n  // single also survived threshold independently (e.g. from a different code path or OCR layout).\n  // Safety: only fires for joins whose continuation starts with /&+:( — digit continuations\n  // like \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki\" are NOT protected, so dedup correctly keeps the shorter form.\n  const survivingJoins = selected.filter((s) => s.origin === \"2-line\" || s.origin === \"3-line\");\n  if (survivingJoins.length > 0) {\n    selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n      if (s.origin !== \"single\") return true;\n      const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n      // Remove PREFIX singles whose continuation join also survived\n      const isPrefixOfJoin = survivingJoins.some((j) => {\n        const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n        if (!jLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \")) return false;\n        const remainder = jLower.slice(sLower.length + 1);\n        return /^[/&+:(]/.test(remainder);\n      });\n      if (isPrefixOfJoin) return false;\n      // Remove SUFFIX singles (e.g. \"& Coriander\") whose parent join also survived\n      const isSuffixOfJoin = survivingJoins.some((j) => {\n        const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n        if (!jLower.endsWith(\" \" + sLower)) return false;\n        // Only remove if the suffix starts with a continuation character\n        return /^[/&+:(]/.test(sLower);\n      });\n      if (isSuffixOfJoin) return false;\n      return true;\n    });\n  }\n\n  // Deduplicate: if one title is a substring of another, keep the shorter (more focused) one.\n  // DO NOT CHANGE THIS LOGIC — it has been incorrectly \"improved\" by the title-loop 5 times.\n  // The tests require shorter wins: \"Pierogi Ruskie\" over \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\".\n  // The pre-filter above handles the conflicting case (structural heading prefix removal) so that\n  // the incomplete prefix line is never present here when the complete join is in selected.\n  selected = selected.filter((a) => {\n    const aLower = a.text.toLowerCase();\n    return !selected.some(\n      (b) =>\n        b !== a &&\n        aLower.includes(b.text.toLowerCase()) &&\n        b.text.length < a.text.length\n    );\n  });\n\n  // Multi-title guard: only join multiple candidates with \"+\" when there is\n  // structural evidence of a multi-recipe page (≥2 ALL_CAPS headings).\n  // A single ALL_CAPS title among mixed-case survivors is a single-recipe page —\n  // collapse to the highest-scoring candidate.\n  // Zero ALL_CAPS survivors → mixed-case multi-title page → keep all.\n  if (selected.length > 1) {\n    const allCapsSelected = selected.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n    if (allCapsSelected.length >= 2) {\n      // Check whether non-first ALL_CAPS headings are section headers within one recipe\n      // (followed immediately by ingredient-like content) rather than separate recipe titles.\n      // A multi-recipe page has body text between titles; a single-recipe page has\n      // ingredient lines immediately after each section heading.\n      const sortedCaps = [...allCapsSelected].sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position);\n      const isSubHeader = sortedCaps.slice(1).every((cap) => {\n        const nextLines = lines.slice(cap.position + 1, cap.position + 3);\n        return nextLines.some(\n          (l) => looksLikeIngredient(l.trim()) || /^\\s*\\d/.test(l.trim())\n        );\n      });\n      if (isSubHeader) {\n        selected = [sortedCaps[0]];\n      } else {\n        selected = allCapsSelected;\n      }\n    } else if (allCapsSelected.length === 1) {\n      selected = [selected.reduce((a, b) => (a.score > b.score ? a : b))];\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Cap at 3, sort by document position\n  selected.sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position);\n  selected = selected.slice(0, 3);\n\n  if (selected.length === 0) {\n    return undefined;\n  }\n\n  return selected.map((s) => s.text).join(\" + \");\n}\n\n/**\n * Extract potential recipe title from OCR text (sync heuristic fallback)\n */\nexport function extractTitle(text: string): string | undefined {\n  if (!text || text.trim().length === 0) {\n    return undefined;\n  }\n\n  const lines = text.split(\"\\n\").map((line) => line.trim());\n\n  for (const line of lines) {\n    if (line.length === 0) continue;\n    if (line.length < 3 || line.length > 50) continue;\n    if (looksLikeIngredient(line)) continue;\n    if (isAllCaps(line)) continue;\n    if (startsWithNumber(line)) continue;\n    return line;\n  }\n\n  return undefined;\n}\n","numLines":560,"startLine":1,"totalLines":560}}}
