idates for the recipe lines. The single-line option passes all filters, and joining the first two lines also works since there's no sentence boundary breaking them apart. But when I try combining three lines including the ingredient quantity, that starts to look problematic. Looking at the 2-line join \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" at 48 characters, it passes the hard filters. Since the lowercase version contains both title words, I'm marking it as a title with a raw score of [0.9, 0.1, 0].\n\nNow checking if this qualifies as a structural heading: it's all caps with 8 words, and most of them have more than one letter. But \"Z\" only has a single letter, so it doesn't meet the threshold for significant words in the structural heading check.\n\nOnce I filter out single-letter words, I'm left with five candidates that all have at least 4 letters each, which means this two-line join does qualify as a structural heading. I'm collecting these into my structural candidates list, starting with the full phrase at 0.8 score, then the shorter variations.\n\nNow I'm applying the reduction logic with Fix 3 to compare these candidates pairwise. When I compare the longest phrase against the shorter ones, the word count difference becomes the deciding factor since their scores are identical—the algorithm picks the shorter candidate when word counts differ, but keeps the longer one when comparing it against an even longer variant.\n\nThis creates a problem: the 8-word joined phrase wins as the best structural heading, but it's actually the wrong choice because it's just concatenating two separate items rather than selecting the most appropriate single heading.\n\nNow I'm checking if there's a continuation character that would extend this heading further—looking for structural candidates that start with the base heading text followed by a space and a continuation marker like \"/\" or \"&\". Since none exist, the firstStructuralHeading stays as the base heading itself.\n\nAn 8-word join with a raw score of 0.8 qualifies for a structural bonus of 0.10 and gets added to the selected results. Then the prefix filter kicks in, removing any candidates that are prefixes of the base heading—so \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" gets filtered out since it's a prefix, but \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" remains because it doesn't match the prefix pattern.\n\nNow I'm checking whether individual terms like \"CHLEBEK\" pass the threshold. With a raw score of -0.4, it falls well below the required threshold of around 0.616, so it doesn't make the cut. I'm also considering how \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" combines with other text like \"500 g strączków zielonego groszku\" and whether that joined variant passes the filtering criteria. The real problem is that Fix 3's word-count tiebreaker can't distinguish between a single-line structural heading and a multi-line join that happens to have more words, so it incorrectly picks the joined version. I need to either restrict the tiebreaker to only apply when both candidates are from single lines, or adjust how it's bounded.\n\nRefining the approach: the tiebreaker should prefer more words, but only for single-origin candidates—multi-line joins shouldn't be able to beat single-line structural headings just by having more words. I'm modifying the logic to check the origin type before applying the word-count preference.\n\nModifying the tiebreaker logic... I see the current rewritten thinking ends mid-code with a code block. The next thinking is continuing to trace through the reduce logic with specific examples of how the comparison function handles different heading combinations.\n\nSince the current rewritten thinking already contains code and the next thinking is continuing to work through the logic with examples, I should switch to prose and describe what's being verified:\n\nNow I'm tracing through how the reduce function processes these headings in order, comparing each candidate against the accumulated result