with \"chlebek\", not \"warzywa\".\n\nNow in the deduplication step, I notice that \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" appears as a substring within \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM WARZYWA I BOCZEK\", so the shorter one wins and the longer candidate gets removed. This leaves just \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\", which matches the test failure—the current word-count tiebreaker approach is selecting the wrong candidate as the best structural match.\n\nThe solution is to add a single-origin preference to the tiebreaker so that single-line structural headings rank higher than multi-line joins when their scores are equal. I need to verify whether `structuralCandidates` even contains multi-line joins by checking the origin types, and then for cases like SAFFRON where a single-line heading has a continuation join, the continuation detection logic should properly identify when a join starting with `/&+:(` is a valid continuation and promote it to `firstStructuralHeading`.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2718,"cache_read_input_tokens":43532,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2718},"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"84856199-2e39-4e5f-88ee-7f061b951e03","uuid":"c1bfe271-7d48-4bec-ac4e-1aa825eb86e5"}
