tem with no shorter substring match.\n\nNow I'm checking the pre-dedup logic for that combined entry—it's all caps, positioned at line 0, and the next lines include \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" (not an ingredient) followed by \"500 g strączków zielonego groszku\" which starts with a digit, so it gets flagged as followed by ingredients.\n\nLooking at whether there's a longer parent candidate containing the full join—there isn't one, so it survives the pre-dedup phase. After the actual dedup runs, both individual titles remain while the join gets removed. Then the multi-title guard kicks in with 2 all-caps candidates, checking if \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" at position 1 qualifies as a subheader based on what comes after it.\n\nBut wait—the test result shows both titles in the output, which means either the join itself is what's being returned, or I'm misunderstanding how the selected list is being built. Let me reconsider whether the multi-title guard is actually working with the joined candidate rather than just the individual ones. I'm checking the multi-title guard logic where it identifies \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" as a subheader since the next line starts with a digit, which should filter it out and leave only \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" — but the test is still returning the longer combined string, so something in my trace must be off.\n\nNow I'm looking at the `scoredForThreshold` computation to see if candidates are getting removed there. The bilingual pre-threshold check filters out non-all-caps position-0 items, but since both candidates are all-caps, nothing gets filtered. The threshold is calculated from the best threshold score, which for \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" is 0.8 plus...\n\nCalculating threshold scores for each candidate: the first two candidates score 0.88, the three-word join also scores 0.88, but \"CHLEBEK\" alone drops to -0.32. I need to verify which candidates actually pass the hard filters in the first place to understand the full picture.\n\nWait, I think the real issue is simpler—after applying the single-origin tiebreaker, the best structural heading is \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\", and then I'm checking if there's a structural heading that starts with the base heading text followed by a delimiter character like a slash or ampersand.\n\nLooking at the 2-line join \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM WARZYWA I BOCZEK\", it passes the structural heading check and the prefix match, but fails the delimiter test because \"warzywa i boczek\" starts with \"w\", not one of the expected continuation characters. So that join gets rejected and the base heading stands.\n\nNow I'm calculating the scoring threshold and applying bonuses—the base heading \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" qualifies for the structural bonus of 0.10, and I need to work through the full score formula with its raw score and position factor to see how it ranks against other candidates. Looking at the scoring calculations, all three results exceed the threshold, but I'm noticing the joined string \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" is appearing as the final result instead of being filtered out. Let me trace through the deduplication logic to see why it's not being removed.\n\nChecking the dedup filter... I'm checking whether Fix 2 might have already removed \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" before the dedup logic runs. Looking at the conditions: it's all caps, positioned at line 0, and the next lines include \"500 g strączków zielonego groszku\" which starts with a digit, so `followedByIngredients` would be true. Now I need to verify if there's a longer candidate that contains this substring. I see the deduplication logic is backwards—after Fix 2 filters out the real title, the remaining candidates get deduplicated, but since \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" is longer and contains \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\", the shorter one gets removed instead, leaving only the corrupted longer version as the final result. I'm checking whether \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" is also being filtered out by the pre-deduplication logic. For this entry at position 1, it's all caps and followed by ingredient lines starting with digits, so it should qualify for removal if there's a longer parent candidate containing it—but \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" has \"warzywami\" instead of \"warzywa\", so the substring match might not be working as expected.\n\nActually, the full phrase does contain \"warzywa i boczek\" at the end, so it counts as a longer parent and gets removed too. After Fix 2 filters out both shorter variants, only \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" remains, and the deduplication step keeps it since nothing shorter is a substring of it.\n\nBut this reveals the real problem with Fix 2 — it's checking if ANY line in the next 2 lines looks like an ingredient, even when those lines are separated by structural headings. The \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" at position 0 gets flagged because \"500 g...\" appears 2 lines down, but that's misleading since \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" is a heading in between, not part of the ingredient list. The check needs to be stricter about what counts as a direct ingredient follow-up. I need to narrow the lookahead window from 2 lines to just 1 line immediately after the candidate position, since the current logic is incorrectly flagging lines that happen to contain ingredients further down. Testing this with the CHLEBEK example: at position 0, the next line is \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" which isn't an ingredient, so it wouldn't match—but I need to verify this doesn't break the actual CHLEBEK case at position 8 where \"500 g mąki\" immediately follows. not ingredient → followedByIngredients = false → NOT removed ✓\n- \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" (pos 1): lines[2] = \"500 g strączków...\" - starts with digit → followedByIngredients = true. Then hasLongerParent: does \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" contain \"warzywa i boczek\"? YES → removed ✓\n- \"CHLEBEK\" (pos 4): lines[5] = \"500 g mąki\" - starts with digit → followedByIngredients = true. hasLongerParent: does \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" contain \"chlebek\"? YES → removed ✓\n\nWait, \"CHLEBEK\" doesn't even make it into selected because its rawScore of -0.4 falls below the threshold. Let me retrace this with the actual selected items before Fix 2: \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" at position 0, \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" at position 1, and the combined phrase at position 0. For the first item, it's all caps and followed by a non-ingredient line, so it stays. For \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\"... After deduplication, I'm left with just \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" as the final candidate. The multi-title guard doesn't trigger since there's only one option. I realize the fix needs to adjust the lookahead from 2 lines down to 1 line to prevent this over-matching behavior. I'm verifying that a 1-line lookahead works for both test cases and the real document examples—checking \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" followed immediately by ingredient lines, and \"CHLEBEK\" with the same pattern. The multi-title guard's isSubHeader check uses 2-line lookahead and was working before, so switching to 1-line for this fix should be safer. Let me apply that change now.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2877,"cache_read_input_tokens":54689,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2877},"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"84856199-2e39-4e5f-88ee-7f061b951e03","uuid":"496af673-8ba0-45a3-93f4-acbea72829c9"}
